1 Task 1: Data Source

The data used in this study are from the survey data collected by the US National Center for Health Statistics. NHANES is unique in collecting person-level demographic, health, and nutrition information from personal interviews (interview) and a standardized physical examination in a mobile examination center (MEC). The examination includes objective measures of health status, including height, weight, blood pressure, and the collection of blood and urine specimens for laboratory testing.

Because of the oversampling issue in original data, this NHANES data contains 10,000 rows of data re-sampled from original data to reduce the oversampling issue.

2 Task 2: Load and Tidy the Data

2.1 Data Load

nhanes<- NHANES::NHANES

As originally loaded, the nhanes data contain 10000 rows and 76 columns. We selected out the variables that are most correlated with our outcome about sleep. Since we want to know the sleep quality about subjects who are male and never married, the final data set includes 745 subjects with 12 related variables.

2.2 Select Related Variables

nhanes1<- nhanes%>%
  filter(MaritalStatus == "NeverMarried" & Gender== "male")%>%
  select(ID, Age, BMI,LittleInterest, Depressed,SleepHrsNight,SleepTrouble, PhysActiveDays, AlcoholDay, HealthGen, Pulse, Smoke100)%>%
  mutate(HealthGen = fct_recode(HealthGen,
                                Good="Excellent",
                                Good ="Vgood",
                                Good ="Good",
                                Fair = "Fair",
                                Fair = "Poor"))

For convinence, we merge five levels in variable HealthGen into two difference levels Good and Fair.

Pulse quantitative 60 second pulse rate
Smoke100 binary Yes or No

5 Task 5: My Subjects

The data describe 745 male subjects who never married from survey done by the US National Center for Health Statistics.

6 Task 6: My Variables

  1. Gender
    Gender (sex) of study participant coded as male or female
  2. Age
    Age in years at screening of study participant. Note: Subjects 80 years or older were recorded as 80.
  3. BMI
    Body mass index (weight/height2 in kg/m2). Reported for participants aged 2 years or older.
  4. LittleInterest
    Self-reported number of days where participant had little interest in doing things. Reported for participants aged 18 years or older. One of  None, Several, Majority (more than half the days), or AlmostAll.
  5. Depressed
    Self-reported number of days where participant felt down, depressed or hopeless. Reported for participants aged 18 years or older. One of  None, Several, Majority (more than half the days), or AlmostAll.
  6. SleepHrsNight
    Self-reported number of hours study participant usually gets at night on weekdays or workdays. Reported for participants aged 16 years and older.
  7. SleepTrouble
    Participant has told a doctor or other health professional that they had trouble sleeping. Reported for participants aged 16 years and older. Coded as Yes or No.
  8. PhysActiveDays
    Number of days in a typical week that participant does moderate or vigorous-intensity activity. Reported for participants 12 years or older.
  9. AlcoholDay
    Average number of drinks consumed on days that participant drank alcoholic beverages. Reported for participants aged 18 years or older.
  10. HealthGen
    Self-reported rating of participant’s health in general Reported for participants aged 12 years or older. One of Good, Fair.
  11. Pulse
    60 second pulse rate
  12. Smoke100
    Study participant has smoked at least 100 cigarettes in their entire life. Reported for participants aged 20 years or older as Yes or No.

  • The data set contains 745 observations on 12 variables, well within the limits of 100-1000 observations on 7-20 variables set in the assignment.
  • While we do have some missing values, the number of missing values never exceeds 5, and we have 292 subjects with complete data on all variables, well above the minimum requirement of 100.
  • We are considering at least four predictors for each regression model, and we include at least one quantitative (for example, baseEF) and multi-categorical variable (for example, ecg) in each model.
  • I am certain that it is completely appropriate for these data to be shared with anyone, without any conditions. There are no concerns about privacy or security.

10.3.1 Building the Four Summary Plots

best_mods_1 <- data_frame( k = 2:10,
                           r2 = rs.sum$rsq, adjr2 = rs.sum$adjr2, cp = rs.sum$cp, aic.c = rs.sum$aic.c, bic = rs.sum$bic)
rs.sum <- cbind(best_mods_1, rs.sum$which)
p1<- ggplot(rs.sum, aes(x = k, y = adjr2,label = round(adjr2,2))) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_label() +
  geom_label(data = subset(rs.sum,adjr2 == max(adjr2)),aes(x = k, y = adjr2, label = round(adjr2,2)),
             fill = "yellow", col = "blue") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:10) +
  labs(x = "# of predictors (including intercept)",y = "Adjusted R-squared")

p2<- ggplot(rs.sum, aes(x = k, y = cp,
                   label = round(cp,1))) +
  geom_line() +geom_label() +geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1,col = "red") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:10) +
  labs(x = "# of predictors (including intercept)",y = "Mallows' Cp")

p3<- ggplot(rs.sum, aes(x = k, y = aic.c,label = round(aic.c,1))) +geom_line() +
  geom_label() +geom_label(data = subset(rs.sum, aic.c == min(aic.c)),aes(x = k, y = aic.c), fill = "pink",
                           col = "red") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:10) +labs(x = "# of predictors (including intercept)",y = "Bias-Corrected AIC")

p4<- ggplot(rs.sum, aes(x = k, y = bic,label = round(bic,1))) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_label() +
  geom_label(data = subset(rs.sum, bic == min(bic)),aes(x = k, y = bic),fill = "lightgreen", col = "blue") + theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:10) +
  labs(x = "# of predictors (including intercept)",y = "BIC")
gridExtra::grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, nrow = 2)
